            <h2>Lecture 3: First-Order Differential Equations</h2>
            
            <h3>Reducible to Homogeneous Equations</h3>
            <p>For equations of the form:</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{ax+by+c}{a'x+b'y+c'}$$
            </div>
            
            <div class="case-box">
                <div class="case-title">Case 1: $$\frac{a}{a'} \neq \frac{b}{b'}$$</div>
                <p>Substitute $$x = X+h$$ and $$y = Y+k$$. The equation becomes homogeneous:</p>
                <div class="math-display">
                    $$\frac{dY}{dX} = \frac{aX+bY}{a'X+b'Y}$$
                </div>
                <p>Then substitute $$Y=vX$$.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="case-box">
                <div class="case-title">Case 2: $$\frac{a}{a'} = \frac{b}{b'}$$</div>
                <p>Use substitution, for example, $$t = ax+by$$.</p>
            </div>
            
            <details>
                <summary>Example Problem: $$\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{2x+3y+4}{4x+6y+5}$$</summary>
                <div class="solution">
                    <p>Given: $$(2y+2x+4)dx - (4x+6y+5)dy = 0$$</p>
                    <div class="math-display">
                        $$\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{2x+3y+4}{4x+6y+5}$$
                    </div>
                    <p>Here, $$a=2, a'=4, b=3, b'=6$$.</p>
                    <div class="math-display">
                        $$\frac{a}{a'} = \frac{2}{4} = \frac{1}{2} \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{b}{b'} = \frac{3}{6} = \frac{1}{2}$$
                    </div>
                    <p>Since $$\frac{a}{a'} = \frac{b}{b'}$$, this is Case 2.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <p>Let $$t = 2x+3y$$. Differentiating:</p>
                    <div class="math-display">
                        $$\frac{dt}{dx} = 2 + 3\frac{dy}{dx} \implies \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{dt}{dx} - 2\right)$$
                    </div>
                    <p>Substituting into the original equation:</p>
                    <div class="math-display">
                        $$\frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{dt}{dx} - 2\right) = \frac{t+4}{2t+5}$$
                    </div>
                    <p>After simplification:</p>
                    <div class="math-display">
                        $$\frac{dt}{dx} = \frac{7t+22}{2t+5}$$
                    </div>
                    <p>Separating variables and integrating leads to the solution.</p>
                </div>
            </details>
            
